JSX

react.gg
JSX

If I were to ask you "What is a React Component?", it wouldn't be unreasonable for you to say something like a function that returns some UI. And if that were your answer, though directionally correct, technically you'd be wrong.

The more accurate description would be a function that returns a description of the UI. Though that seems pedantic, it's an important distinction.

For the former to be true, we'd have to be returning literal HTML. Clearly that's not the case because we can't literally have HTML inside of a JavaScript file. But if we're not returning HTML, what exactly are we returning?

Meet JSX

The magic behind having HTML-ish looking syntax directly inside of your JavaScript files

export default function WhatIsJSX () {
return <main>
<h1>This is JSX</h1>
<h2>JSX <i>looks</i> like HTML</h2>
<h4>(but it's not)</h4>
<p>
JSX is inspired by HTML and allows you to
write HTML-ish looking syntax inside your
React Components.
</p>
</main>
}

For the most part, writing JSX should feel pretty natural. It's mostly just like HTML, but there are a few things to be aware of. We'll spend the rest of this post exploring some of those gotchas as well as some tips and tricks when it comes to JSX.

First, let's talk about having multi-line JSX.

Up until this point, whenever we've had multiple elements in our JSX, we've done something like this – where the first element immediately follow the return and the rest are indented normally on new lines.

export default function WhatIsJSX () {
  return <main>
    <h1>This is JSX</h1>
    <h2>JSX <i>looks</i> like HTML</h2>
    <h4>(but it's not)</h4>
    <p>
      JSX is inspired by HTML and allows you to
      write HTML-ish looking syntax inside your
      React Components.
    </p>
  </main>
}

Though that works, admittedly it's a little weird. Specifically, it's the first <main> that feels off. We would never write HTML with the first element indented more than its children elements, so why do it here?

To fix this, you might be tempted to do something like this (which feels more natural).

export default function WhatIsJSX () {
  return 
    <main>
      <h1>This is JSX</h1>
      <h2>JSX <i>looks</i> like HTML</h2>
      <h4>(but it's not)</h4>
      <p>
        JSX is inspired by HTML and allows you to
        write HTML-ish looking syntax inside your
        React Components.
      </p>
    </main>
}

Unfortunately, as you can see, that won't work. It's a fun quirk of the JavaScript specification. When the JavaScript interpreter runs this code, because of automatic semicolon insertion (ASI), it'll insert a semicolon right after our return statement – ending the function and returning nothing, like this.

export default function WhatIsJSX () {
  return;
    // <main>
    //   <h1>This is JSX</h1>
    //   <h2>JSX <i>looks</i> like HTML</h2>
    //   <h4>(but it's not)</h4>
    //   <p>
    //     JSX is inspired by HTML and allows you to
    //     write HTML-ish looking syntax inside your
    //     React Components.
    //   </p>
    // </main>
}

The standard way to fix this is to wrap your JSX inside of parens (), which allows us to have our JSX indented as you'd expect, while avoiding ASI issues.

export default function WhatIsJSX () {
  return (
    <main>
      <h1>This is JSX</h1>
      <h2>JSX <i>looks</i> like HTML</h2>
      <h4>(but it's not)</h4>
      <p>
        JSX is inspired by HTML and allows you to
        write HTML-ish looking syntax inside your
        React Components.
      </p>
    </main>
  )
}

So far so good, but here's a question I want you to think through. Can you spot any issues with this component?

export default function Authors () {
  return (
    <h2>Authors</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Tyler McGinnis</li>
      <li>Ben Adam</li>
      <li>Alex Brown</li>
    </ul>
  )
}

It looks fine, right? Unfortunately, it'll throw an error as seen below.

export default function Authors () {
  return (
    <h2>Authors</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Tyler McGinnis</li>
      <li>Ben Adam</li>
      <li>Alex Brown</li>
    </ul>
  )
}

Something went wrong

Cannot assign to read only property 'message' of object 'SyntaxError: /App.jsx: Adjacent JSX elements must be wrapped in an enclosing tag. Did you want a JSX fragment <>...</>? (4:4) 2 | return ( 3 | <h2>Authors</h2> > 4 | <ul> | ^ 5 | <li>Tyler McGinnis</li> 6 | <li>Ben Adam</li> 7 | <li>Alex Brown</li>'

That's a fancy way to say that you can only ever return one top-level element from a component. In our example, we're trying to return 2 (h2, and ul).

To fix this, as the error says, we want to return one, which we can do by wrapping everything in a div.

export default function Authors () {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Authors</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Tyler McGinnis</li>
        <li>Ben Adam</li>
        <li>Alex Brown</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  )
}

That fixes the issue, but now we have a semantic problem.

Now we're unnecessarily creating an extra div. This is the exact use case that React.Fragment was created for. If you want to return adjacent elements but don't want to change your markup, wrap them in <React.Fragment>.

import * as React from "react"

export default function Authors () {
  return (
    <React.Fragment>
      <h2>Authors</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Tyler McGinnis</li>
        <li>Ben Adam</li>
        <li>Alex Brown</li>
      </ul>
    </React.Fragment>
  )
}

Much better.

There also exists a shorthand syntax for React Fragment (<>), but it feels a little too magical to me, so I don't use it much.

export default function Authors () {
  return (
    <>
      <h2>Authors</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Tyler McGinnis</li>
        <li>Ben Adam</li>
        <li>Alex Brown</li>
      </ul>
    </>
  )
}

Let's do another one. Can you spot what's wrong with this JSX?

function Form () {
  return (
    <form method="get" action="/search">
      <img src="search.png" alt="search icon">
      <br>
      <label>
        Search
        <input name="term" type="text">
      </label>
      <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>
  )
}

If you're familiar with HTML but new to React, your answer is probably "...nothing?" This is another case where JSX is slightly different than the HTML spec. Whenever you have a "Self-closing tag" (the most popular being input, br, and img), you need to make sure that you explicitly close them.

<input> 👎
<input /> 👍


<br> 👎
<br /> 👍


<img> 👎
<img /> 👍

So with that, our Form component will now have valid JSX if we explicitly close all our self-closing elements.

function Form () {
  return (
    <form method="get" action="/search">
      <img src="search.png" alt="search icon" />
      <br />
      <label>
        Search
        <input name="term" type="text" />
      </label>
      <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>
  )
}

How about this one? Can you spot what's wrong with this JSX?

function Avatar () {
  return (
    <img
      src="avatar.png"
      alt="Avatar"
      class="avatar"
    />
  )
}

I know, this is a weird one. The error is that class should be className.

function Avatar () {
  return (
    <img
      src="avatar.png"
      alt="Avatar"
      className="avatar"
    />
  )
}

The reason for this is because, as you know, eventually this JSX gets converted into JavaScript, and in JavaScript, there are particular keywords that are reserved (meaning you can't use them). class just happens to be one of those.

🤨
"WTF I thought you said JSX was just like HTML?"- You, probably.

A similar thing to look out for is that you can't have variable names that have a - in them. So any normal HTML attributes that have a - in them (like stroke-width) you need to convert to camelCase.

function Icon () {
  return (
    <svg width="200" height="200">
      <rect
        x="10"
        y="10"
        width="180"
        height="180"
        fill="none"
        stroke="black"
        strokeWidth="5"
      />
    </svg>
  )
}

Whenever you want to use an expression (something that produces a value) in JSX, you need to wrap the expression in single curly braces, {}.

function Welcome {
  const name = 'Tyler'


  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Hello, {name}</h1>
      <p>
        Today is {new Date().toLocaleDateString()}
      </p>
      <p>What is 2 + 2? {2 + 2}</p>
    </div>
  )
}

If you want a React component to show nothing, as sometimes is the case when data is still loading, return null from your component.

if (isLoading() === true) {
  return null
}


return (
  <main>
    <h1>This is JSX</h1>
    <h2>JSX <i>looks</i> like HTML</h2>
  </main>
)

Next is conditional rendering.

The ability to conditionally show UI based on a piece of state is pretty foundational to any front-end framework. Typically, this functionality is built natively into the framework.

// Angular
<h1 *ngIf="authed; else elseBlock">Welcome back!</h1>
<ng-template #elseBlock>
  <h1>Login to see your dashboard</h1>
</ng-template>


// Vue
<h1 v-if="authed">Welcome back!</h1>
<h1 v-else>Login to see your dashboard</h1>

With React, it's a bit different. Instead of increasing the API surface layer, because JSX is Just JavaScript, React can leverage native JavaScript features to accomplish the same task. There are pros and cons to this approach, but if you're already familiar with conditional rendering in JavaScript, you'll feel pretty comfortable.

The most basic example is just using a simple if/else statement.

function Dashboard () {
  const authed = isAuthed()


  if (authed === true) {
    return <h1>Welcome back!</h1>
  } else {
    return <h1>Login to see your dashboard</h1>
  }
}

Again, because we're just writing JavaScript, if we had another condition, we'd just add an else if case.

function Dashboard () {
  const authed = isAuthed()
  const firstLogin = isNew()


  if (firstLogin === true) {
    return <h1>👋 Welcome!</h1>
  } else if (authed === true) {
    return <h1>Welcome back!</h1>
  } else {
    return  <h1>Login to see your dashboard</h1>
  }
}

If you're rendering different UI based on a single condition, typically you'd use JavaScript's ternary operator.

function Dashboard () {
  return isAuthed() === true
    ? <h1>Welcome back!</h1>
    : <h1>Login to see your dashboard</h1>
}

We learned earlier that any expression needs to be wrapped in {}. We can use that knowledge to render a ternary inside of JSX.

function Dashboard () {
  return (
    <React.Fragment>
      <Logo />
      {isAuthed() === true
        ? <h1>Welcome back!</h1>
        : <h1>Login to see your dashboard</h1>}
    </React.Fragment>
  )
}

Earlier we also learned that we can return null if we want React to render nothing. This is a common pattern when using ternaries.

function Dashboard () {
  return (
    <React.Fragment>
      <Logo />
      {showWarning() === true
        ? <Warning />
        : null}
    </React.Fragment>
  )
}

Another common use case of conditional rendering is using JavaScript's logical && operator. If you're not already familiar with it, typically it's used in conditionals as an "AND" statement.

if (user && authed) {
  // runs if user and authed are truthy
}

In the example above, it's important to note that authed won't be checked if user isn't truthy. Using that logic, we can use the && operator as a more concise ternary that renders null.

function Dashboard () {
  return (
    <React.Fragment>
      <Logo />
      {showWarning() === true && <Warning />}
    </React.Fragment>
  )
}

Now one question you may have had is how does React know the difference between a custom React component like <User /> and a native HTML element like <span>? The answer is probably simpler than you'd expect, it's based on the capitalization.

Whenever you create a React component, you need to capitalize it. Otherwise, React will think it's a native HTML element.

At this point we're almost done, but there's one more thing about JSX we need to cover.

Eventually you come to accept that as an app developer, your primary job is to render lists. It's so fundamental, that most frameworks come with a special API to accomplish it.

// Vue
<ul id="tweets">
  <li v-for="tweet in tweets">
    {{ tweet.text }}
  </li>
</ul>
// Angular
<ul id="tweets">
  <li *ngFor="let tweet of tweets">
    {{ tweet.text }}
  </li>
</ul>

React takes a different approach. When possible, React tries to keep the API surface to a minimum. To do that, it relies heavily on features that JavaScript provides out of the box.

When rendering a list, the end goal, as seen in the Vue and Angular examples above, is to create a list of <li> elements that we can then show to the UI. Can you think of anything built into JavaScript itself that would help us accomplish this? What about .map?

Typically you use .map when you need to create a new array, based on a previous array. Something like this.

const tweets = [
  {
    id: 1,
    stars: 13,
    text: 'Turns out git reset --hard HEAD^ was a terrible idea',
  },
  {
    id: 3,
    stars: 51,
    text: "Clean code is subjective. Optimize for deletion",
  },
  {
    id: 4,
    stars: 19,
    text: "What even is a jQuery?",
  },
]


const stars = tweets.map((tweet) =>
  tweet.stars
) // [13,51,19]

Except now, instead of creating a new array of stars, we want to create a new array of <li>s. Using the same .map method, let's throw in some JSX.

import tweets from "./tweets"

export default function Tweets () {
  return (
    <ul id="tweets">
      {tweets.map((tweet) => (
        <li>{tweet.text}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  )
}

Notice there's no new API you need to remember. If you can remember how .map works, you can remember how to create a list in React.

Unfortunately, we're not quite done yet. There's just one small addition we need to make to our code. Whenever you use .map to create a list in React, you need to make sure that you add a unique key prop to each list item.

<ul id="tweets">
  {tweets.map((tweet) => (
    <li key={tweet.id}>{tweet.text}</li>
  ))}
</ul>

It's React's job to make rendering the list as fast as possible. When you give each list item a unique key prop, it helps React know which items, if any, change throughout different renders of that component.

🧐

WTF is JSX *actually*?

For the curious amongst you, you're probably wondering how JSX actually works. We have an entire bonus section later on dedicated to this question, but here's a quick teaser.

Like most magic, the answer is more simple than you might expect.

In order to use React, at build time, you need a tool to transform JSX into normal JavaScript the browser can understand.

So for example, a component like this

function Hello () {
  return <h1>Hello World</h1>
}

at build time will be compiled to regular JavaScript like this

import { jsx as _jsx } from "react/jsx-runtime"


function Hello() {
  return _jsx("h1", {
    children: "Hello World"
  })
}

so the browser only ever sees JavaScript.

tl;dr – JSX is just JavaScript*

*eventually

As far as I understand, the primary reason we use className instead of class in React is because it aligns with the JavaScript DOM API. In JavaScript, className is the property used on DOM elements to assign their class, not class. While it's correct that class is a reserved keyword in JavaScript, the main reason for React's use of className is to ensure proper interaction with the DOM.

This can be a common point of confusion, as JSX syntax closely resembles HTML, where we typically use class to assign CSS classes to elements. However, when working with React and JSX, we use className in accordance with the JavaScript DOM API. As much as I know, this is the main reason behind the usage of className instead of class.

I hope this information helps to clear up any misunderstandings. Keep up the great work with your course, I'm finding it very beneficial and I'm looking forward to the next lessons!
